            <i>
              The program comes in response to an executive decree issued by
              Trump, which sought to stem illegal immigration into the US.
              Credits: Economic Times
            </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            The US government is testing a
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #4d3060;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-5-aug-25-spotlight-h2-8-12-month-visa-bond-pilot-program?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >12-month visa bond pilot program</a
            >
            requiring some foreign travelers to pay a refundable bond of up to
            $15,000 to visit the US for
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #4d3060;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-5-aug-25-spotlight-h2-9-business-b-1?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >business (B-1)</a
            >
            or
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #4d3060;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-5-aug-25-spotlight-h2-10-tourism-b-2?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >tourism (B-2)</a
            >. The bond is refunded if the traveler leaves before their visa
            expires. This program applies to visitors from countries with high
            visa overstay levels or weak screening systems.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            The specific countries have not been named yet, but will be
            announced 15 days before implementation and updated on a rolling
            basis. It does not apply to travelers under the
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #4d3060;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-5-aug-25-spotlight-h2-11-visa-waiver-program?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >Visa Waiver Program</a
            >, which exempts 41 designated countries. A
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #4d3060;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-5-aug-25-spotlight-h2-12-2024-report?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >2024 report</a
            >
            revealed that over 300,000 business and tourist visitors overstayed
            their visas in fiscal year 2023, highlighting abuse of existing
            provisions.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            The Trump administration described this move as a ‚Äútool of
            diplomacy‚Äù to encourage countries to vet their citizens before
            travel, discourage abuse of Citizenship-by-Investment programs, and
            prompt strict measures from governments whose citizens repeatedly
            overstay US visas. Critics argue this measure will deter tourism,
            reduce judicial visits, and hurt US trade.
          </p>
