            who fled the state in protest of the redistricting efforts. He
            claimed that absentee House Democrats may have violated bribery laws
            by soliciting or accepting funds to restrict legislative duties.
            Democrats who fled the state were holding various events across the
            state while skipping the redistricting voting.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            The
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #4d3060;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-5-aug-25-spotlight-h3-14-texas-constitution?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >Texas Constitution</a
            >
            allows the House to force absent members to return using civil
            arrest, not criminal charges. However, these civil warrants are
            enforceable within Texas state lines, rendering them
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #4d3060;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-5-aug-25-spotlight-h3-15-largely-symbolic?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >largely symbolic</a
            >
            once lawmakers exit the state. The Texas House Democratic Caucus
            Chair said that the governor has no authority to arrest the
            Democrats, but is uncertain of how Trump is going to respond or
            escalate the standoff.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            With 150 total seats, the House requires a
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #4d3060;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-5-aug-25-spotlight-h3-16-two-thirds-majority?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >two-thirds majority</a
            >
            to be present to approve the redistricting bill. About 57 out of 61
            Democrats have left the state, disturbing the quorum and blocking
            the Republicans from proceeding with the plan. Texas Democrats are
            within their procedural rights to flee and deny quorum.
          </p>
